vectorData.altText: That's right! Notice at the open medulla the pyramids ventrally and the inferior cerebellar peduncles reaching posterolaterally. Notice also the fourth ventricle and the olives.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

In Functional Neuroanatomy, in the Spinal Cord and Brainstem series, compare sections 9 (rostral medulla) and 8 (caudal medulla) to the axon-stained sections of the rostral and caudal medulla that I provided.  In these sections identify the pyramids ventrally. 
In section 9 (rostral midbrain), also identify the olives lateral to the pyramids, and the inferior cerebellar peduncles “reaching” posterolaterally toward the cerebellum.
Identify these same features in Transverse Series sections 3 (rostral medulla ) and 2 (caudal medulla). 
This characteristic shape with the pyramids ventrally, and at more rostral levels, the olives lateral to the pyramids and the inferior cerebellar peduncles “reaching” posteriorly, identifies the medulla in MRI.
Be sure you can identify features A through D. See answers here     .

Answer Key
pyramids / corticospinal tract
olives
inf. cerebellar peduncles
fourth ventricle
gracile tubercle / fasciculus gracilis
cuneate tubercle / fasciculus cuneatus
central canal
With reference to the illustrations of the brainstem provided, the brainstem model, and your brainstem specimens, identify surface features and spaces A through G.

The fourth ventricle is associated with the rostral midbrain. It is an expanded, or “open” portion of the ventricular system, as compared to the narrow central canal seen at the caudal, or “closed” medulla.
